body:
This is a proposition to easier event programming in Groovy. The feature is inspired from [C#'s Event Handler](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ms366768.aspx) feature syntax and aims to be very similar to Qt's signals and slots feature to exchange messages between objects in an event-driven programming style. This is an idea I've had while working on [an android application written in Groovy](https://github.com/AugierLe42e/Pheobius)

Please note this is a very early work and I'm completely new in contributing to Groovy so please forgive me if I make big mistakes. I'm opening it very soon to have an early feedback.

The current system works like this :

```
class ObjectWithEvent{
    // Declare the event
    public Event somethingChanged = new Event()

    public void makeSomething()
    // Code going on and then, something happens, you throw the event
    somethingChanged(newValue)
}

class ObjectListening{
    //
    private ObjectWithEvent objectWithEvent
    public ObjectListening(){
         // Subscribe to the event
         objectWithEvent.somethingChanged += this.&onSomethingChanged
    }

    private void onSomethingChanged(int newValue){
        // Code here
    }
}
```

The main concern I have with the current implementation is the everything or nothing apsect. Either you make the event public but you are able to fire it from everywhere, either you make it private and you are not able to subscribe to it from outside. Maybe you can help me with that.

The other concern I have is the reaction it could have with the `@CompileStatic` anotation for the type of the Closure.

Please tell me if this work interests you.
Thank you.
